  <subsection xml:id="factoring-with-gcf">
    <title>Factoring Trinomials with Common Factors</title>
    <p>
      Sometimes the trinomial is set up so that <m>a \neq 1</m> (the number in front of <m>x^2</m> is not 1), however, there is a common factor that can be factored out, reducing the expression to one which can be factored using the previous method.
    </p>
    <project>
      <title>Factoring with GCF First</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>Factor each quadratic expression completely.</p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p><m>2x^2 - 4x - 70</m>.</p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p><m>2(x-7)(x+5)</m>.</p>
        </answer>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p><m>3x^2 + 30x + 75</m>.</p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p><m>3(x+5)^2</m>.</p>
        </answer>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p><m>3x^2 - 30x + 48</m>.</p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p><m>3(x-8)(x-2)</m>.</p>
        </answer>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p><m>2x^2 - 32x + 128</m>.</p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p><m>2(x-8)^2</m>.</p>
        </answer>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p><m>5x^2 + 10x + 5</m>.</p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p><m>5(x+1)^2</m>.</p>
        </answer>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p><m>6x^2 - 36x + 54</m>.</p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p><m>6(x-3)^2</m>.</p>
        </answer>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p><m>x^3 + 5x^2 - 36x</m>.</p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p><m>x(x+9)(x-4)</m>.</p>
        </answer>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p><m>x^3 + 2x^2 + x</m>.</p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p><m>x(x+1)^2</m>.</p>
        </answer>
      </task>
    </project>
  </subsection>
  
  
  
  <subsection xml:id="factoring-non-monic-quadratics">
    <title>Factoring Polynomials of the form <m>ax^2 + bx + c</m>, <m>a \neq 1</m></title>
    <p>
      There are many methods for factoring these kinds of polynomials. Different teachers will differ in which method they use. All of them end up with the same result, but some are more efficient than others. I personally believe the <em>cross method</em> is the most efficient and easiest method to use.
    </p>
  </subsection>
  
  <subsection xml:id="cross-method">
    <title>The Cross Method</title>
    <example>
      <title>First Cross Method Example</title>
      <p>
        Consider,
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>2x^2 + 7x + 3</mrow>
      </md>
      <p>
        To do the cross method,
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            Draw a crisscross or X shape underneath.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Find two things that multiply to the first term, and two things that multiply to the last term.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Multiply each of the diagonals and add them up.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            The combination is correct if the diagonals add up to the middle term.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        For example,
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>2x^2 + 7x + 3</mrow>
      </md>
      <image width="50%">
        <latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}[baseline=(M.base)]
          \node (M) at (0,0) {$2x$};
          \node (P) at (0,-1) {$x$};
          \node (N) at (1.5,0) {$3$};
          \node (Q) at (1.5,-1) {$1$};
          \draw (M) -- (Q);
          \draw (P) -- (N);
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
      <p>
        On the left side, <m>2x \cdot x = 2x^2</m>, and on the right, <m>3 \times 1 = 3</m>. However, the diagonals add up to <m>2x + 3x = 5x</m>, which isn't the middle term. Instead, switch the 3 and the 1,
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>2x^2 + 7x + 3</mrow>
      </md>
      <image width="50%">
        <latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}[baseline=(M.base)]
          \node (M) at (0,0) {$2x$};
          \node (P) at (0,-1) {$x$};
          \node (N) at (1.5,0) {$1$};
          \node (Q) at (1.5,-1) {$3$};
          \draw (M) -- (Q);
          \draw (P) -- (N);
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
      <p>
        We now get <m>6x + x = 7x</m>, which is the middle term. After you've found the correct combination, the two factors can be read horizontally in each row,
      </p>
      <image width="50%">
        <latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}
          \node (M) at (0,0) {$2x$};
          \node at (0.75,0) {$+$};
          \node (N) at (1.5,0) {$1$};
          \node (P) at (0,-1) {$x$};
          \node at (0.75,-1) {$+$};
          \node (Q) at (1.5,-1) {$3$};
          \node at (-0.4, 0) {$($};
          \node at (-0.4, -1) {$($};
          \node at (1.9, 0) {$)$};
          \node at (1.9, -1) {$)$};
          \draw (M) -- (Q);
          \draw (P) -- (N);
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
      <md>
        <mrow> = (2x + 1)(x + 3)</mrow>
      </md>
    </example>
    <example>
      <title>Cross Method with Negatives</title>
      <p>
        Consider,
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>3x^2 - 5x - 2</mrow>
      </md>
      <p>
        Using the cross method, one possible combination is,
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>3x^2 - 5x - 2</mrow>
      </md>
      <image width="50%">
        <latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}[baseline=(M.base)]
          \node (M) at (0,0) {$3x$};
          \node (P) at (0,-1) {$x$};
          \node (N) at (1.5,0) {$2$};
          \node (Q) at (1.5,-1) {$-1$};
          \draw (M) -- (Q);
          \draw (P) -- (N);
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
      <p>
        On the left side, <m>3x \cdot x = 3x^2</m>, and on the right, <m>2 \cdot (-1) = -2</m>. However, the diagonals add up to <m>-3x + 2x = -x</m>, which isn't the middle term, so this isn't correct. Instead, switch the 2 and the <m>-1</m>,
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>3x^2 - 5x - 2</mrow>
      </md>
      <image width="50%">
        <latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}[baseline=(M.base)]
          \node (M) at (0,0) {$3x$};
          \node (P) at (0,-1) {$x$};
          \node (N) at (1.5,0) {$-1$};
          \node (Q) at (1.5,-1) {$2$};
          \draw (M) -- (Q);
          \draw (P) -- (N);
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
      <p>
        Now the diagonals add to <m>6x - x = 5x</m>, which is not quite <m>-5x</m>, but it's close. To fix it, just change the negative sign on the right to be on the 2 instead of the 1,
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>3x^2 - 5x - 2</mrow>
      </md>
      <image width="50%">
        <latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}[baseline=(M.base)]
          \node (M) at (0,0) {$3x$};
          \node (P) at (0,-1) {$x$};
          \node (N) at (1.5,0) {$1$};
          \node (Q) at (1.5,-1) {$-2$};
          \draw (M) -- (Q);
          \draw (P) -- (N);
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
      <p>
        Now the diagonals add up to <m>-6x + x = -5x</m>, which matches the middle term. Reading across gives the factors:
      </p>
      <image width="50%">
        <latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}
          \node (M) at (0,0) {$3x$};
          \node at (0.75,0) {$+$};
          \node (N) at (1.5,0) {$1$};
          \node (P) at (0,-1) {$x$};
          \node at (0.75,-1) {$+$};
          \node (Q) at (1.5,-1) {$-2$};
          \node at (-0.4, 0) {$($};
          \node at (-0.4, -1) {$($};
          \node at (1.9, 0) {$)$};
          \node at (1.9, -1) {$)$};
          \draw (M) -- (Q);
          \draw (P) -- (N);
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
      <md>
        <mrow> = (3x + 1)(x - 2)</mrow>
      </md>
    </example>
    <example>
      <title>Cross Method with Trial and Error</title>
      <p>
        Consider,
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>6x^2 + 19x + 10</mrow>
      </md>
      <p>
        For the left side, we have 6, which means we could choose 6 and 1, or 3 and 2. We don't know ahead of time which will be correct, so let's choose 6 and 1, and we can change it later.
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>6x^2 + 19x + 10</mrow>
      </md>
      <image width="50%">
        <latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}[baseline=(M.base)]
          \node (M) at (0,0) {$6x$};
          \node (P) at (0,-1) {$x$};
          \node (N) at (1.5,0) {$2$};
          \node (Q) at (1.5,-1) {$5$};
          \draw (M) -- (Q);
          \draw (P) -- (N);
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
      <p>
        The diagonals add up to <m>30x + 2x = 32x</m>, which is too large. Let's switch the 2 and 5,
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>6x^2 + 19x + 10</mrow>
      </md>
      <image width="50%">
        <latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}[baseline=(M.base)]
          \node (M) at (0,0) {$6x$};
          \node (P) at (0,-1) {$x$};
          \node (N) at (1.5,0) {$5$};
          \node (Q) at (1.5,-1) {$2$};
          \draw (M) -- (Q);
          \draw (P) -- (N);
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
      <p>
        Now the diagonals are <m>12x + 5x = 17x</m>, which is close but still not 19. Try different factor pairs of 10: <m>1</m> and <m>10</m>.
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>6x^2 + 19x + 10</mrow>
      </md>
      <image width="50%">
        <latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}[baseline=(M.base)]
          \node (M) at (0,0) {$6x$};
          \node (P) at (0,-1) {$x$};
          \node (N) at (1.5,0) {$10$};
          \node (Q) at (1.5,-1) {$1$};
          \draw (M) -- (Q);
          \draw (P) -- (N);
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
      <p>
        Now the diagonals are <m>6x + 10x = 16x</m>, still not enough. Switching gives,
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>6x^2 + 19x + 10</mrow>
      </md>
      <image width="50%">
        <latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}[baseline=(M.base)]
          \node (M) at (0,0) {$6x$};
          \node (P) at (0,-1) {$x$};
          \node (N) at (1.5,0) {$1$};
          \node (Q) at (1.5,-1) {$10$};
          \draw (M) -- (Q);
          \draw (P) -- (N);
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
      <p>
        Now we get <m>60x + x = 61x</m>, too large. We've tried all of the possible combinations on the right side, so this means that the left side is wrong. Letâ€™s try <m>3x</m> and <m>2x</m> instead.
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>6x^2 + 19x + 10</mrow>
      </md>
      <image width="50%">
        <latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}[baseline=(M.base)]
          \node (M) at (0,0) {$3x$};
          \node (P) at (0,-1) {$2x$};
          \node (N) at (1.5,0) {$2$};
          \node (Q) at (1.5,-1) {$5$};
          \draw (M) -- (Q);
          \draw (P) -- (N);
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
      <p>
        Now the diagonals add to <m>15x + 4x = 19x</m>, perfect! Reading across gives,
      </p>
      <image width="50%">
        <latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}
          \node (M) at (0,0) {$3x$};
          \node at (0.75,0) {$+$};
          \node (N) at (1.5,0) {$2$};
          \node (P) at (0,-1) {$2x$};
          \node at (0.75,-1) {$+$};
          \node (Q) at (1.5,-1) {$5$};
          \node at (-0.4, 0) {$($};
          \node at (-0.4, -1) {$($};
          \node at (1.9, 0) {$)$};
          \node at (1.9, -1) {$)$};
          \draw (M) -- (Q);
          \draw (P) -- (N);
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
      <md>
        <mrow> = (3x + 2)(2x + 5)</mrow>
      </md>
    </example>
    <p>
      The cross method requires some guessing and checking (or trial and error), especially at first. However, with some practice and gain experience, you'll become more experienced at making educated guesses for the combinations that are more likely to work, so you won't have to naively go through every single combination. Also, sometimes you get lucky and find the correct combination right away.
    </p>
    <example>
      <p>
        <alert>Using the cross method when <m>a=1</m></alert>. The cross method can also be used in the previous simpler case, when <m>a = 1</m>. For example, for,
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>x^2 - x - 20</mrow>
      </md>
      <p>
        We could think of factors of <m>-20</m> that add up to <m>-1</m>, which are <m>-5</m> and 4, to get,
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow> = (x-5)(x+4)</mrow>
      </md>
      <p>
        However, we can also use the cross method. The first term is <m>x^2</m>, so we can write <m>x</m> and <m>x</m> on the left side, and the last term is <m>-20</m>, so we can try <m>-5</m> and <m>4</m> on the right side. Then, we draw a crisscross or X shape, multiply the diagonals, and add them up. The combination is correct if the diagonals add up to the middle term.
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>x^2 - x - 20</mrow>
      </md>
      <image width="50%">
        <latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}[baseline=(M.base)]
          \node (M) at (0,0) {$x$};
          \node (P) at (0,-1) {$x$};
          \node (N) at (1.5,0) {$-5$};
          \node (Q) at (1.5,-1) {$4$};
          \draw (M) -- (Q);
          \draw (P) -- (N);
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
      <md>
        <mrow> = (x-5)(x+4)</mrow>
      </md>
      <p>
        This gives the same answer as before.
      </p>
    </example>
    <example>
      <title>Factoring out a Negative</title>
      <p>
        <alert>Factor out the negative sign first</alert>. Consider <m>-6x^2 + 17x + 3</m>. In this case, <m>a = -6</m> which is negative, unlike the previous examples. You could continue just like before, by finding two things that multiply to <m>-6x^2</m> and 3. For example,
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>-6x^2 + 17x + 3</mrow>
      </md>
      <image width="50%">
        <latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}[baseline=(M.base)]
          \node (M) at (0,0) {$-3x$};
          \node (P) at (0,-1) {$2x$};
          \node (N) at (1.5,0) {$1$};
          \node (Q) at (1.5,-1) {$3$};
          \draw (M) -- (Q);
          \draw (P) -- (N);
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
      <p>
        This combination doesn't work.
      </p>
      <p>
        However, it turns out that the negative sign on the left side makes things more complicated, because you have to worry about where to put the negative sign on the left side (in addition to the right side being either 3 and 1 or <m>-3</m> and <m>-1</m>). There are a lot of negative signs, and it can get confusing.
      </p>
      <p>
        Instead, it's better to first factor out the negative sign in the front. To do this, factor out <m>-1</m> from all terms, which basically flips the sign of all the terms,
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow> = - \brac{6x^2 - 17x - 3}</mrow>
      </md>
      <p>
        Then, factor the expression inside the brackets as before. Now, you don't need to worry about the sign on the left column, and the only sign choice for the <m>-3</m>, where one of the numbers must be negative.
      </p>
      <me>
        - \brac{6x^2 - 17x - 3}
      </me>
      <image width="50%">
        <latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}[baseline=(M.base)]
          \node (M) at (0,0) {$6x$};
          \node (P) at (0,-1) {$x$};
          \node (N) at (1.5,0) {$1$};
          \node (Q) at (1.5,-1) {$-3$};
          \draw (M) -- (Q);
          \draw (P) -- (N);
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
      <md>
        <mrow> - (6x + 1)(x - 3)</mrow>
      </md>
    </example>
    <p>
      In general, if the <m>a</m> value is negative, factor out <m>-1</m> from all terms first, and then factor the remaining polynomial.
    </p>
    <example>
      <title>Factoring out GCF Before Cross Method</title>
      <p>
        <alert>Factor out the GCF before using the cross method</alert>. Consider,
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>2x^2 - 4x - 30</mrow>
      </md>
      <p>
        Here, we can still use the cross method. However, the numbers are kinda large, especially 30, which has many possibilities for its factors. After some trial and error, the correct combination is,
      </p>
      <image width="50%">
        <latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}[baseline=(M.base)]
          \node (M) at (0,0) {$2x$};
          \node (P) at (0,-1) {$x$};
          \node (N) at (1.5,0) {$-10$};
          \node (Q) at (1.5,-1) {$3$};
          \draw (M) -- (Q);
          \draw (P) -- (N);
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
      <md>
        <mrow> = (2x - 10)(x + 3)</mrow>
      </md>
      <p>
        However, notice that <m>2x - 10</m> also contains a common factor of 2, so we should factor it out also.
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow> = 2(x - 5)(x + 3)</mrow>
      </md>
      <p>
        Instead, it is easier to first factor out the common factor of 2,
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow> 2x^2 - 4x - 30 \amp = 2 \brac{x^2 - 2x - 15}</mrow>
      </md>
      <p>
        Then, factoring the remaining <m>x^2 - 2x - 15</m> only uses the sum and product method, and has smaller numbers to work with,
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow> \amp = 2 (x - 5)(x + 3)</mrow>
      </md>
    </example>
    <p>
      In general, you should first factor out the GCF (greatest common factor), if there is one, before using the cross method. This makes the numbers you have to work with smaller, making it easier to find the factors.
    </p>
